UTF-8 is not locale-dependent. It can represent any Unicode codepoint, used by any language. I don't think the problem lies in the conversion performed by `wcout`. I'd check two things. First, whether the string literal makes its way into the binary intact. Do `wcout << (int)L'П';` - this should print `1055`; if it doesn't, the character is mangled by the compiler. Second, whether the console is set up to display non-English characters. Redirect output to a file, examine it with hex viewer. Cyrillic `'П'` should be represented as two bytes `D0 9F`
